{"type":"message","id":"f5882dcd","parentId":"bdbafe97","timestamp":"2026-03-31T02:35:18.581Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_bbbtfmn77k40_1","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nVideo URL: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=41_TNGDDnfQ\n---\n\nTranscript:\n\nbot is the most powerful AI tool ever released. I say that in every single video and I mean it. In this video, I want to go over six life-changing use cases that you can start using Claudebot for right now. These aren't basic use cases. These are advanced workflows that will completely transform how you work and think about AI agents. If you stick with me until the end, I'll show you the single most important use case that you need to implement immediately. Let's get into it. The first use case I want to talk about is using Claudebot as a 24/7 researcher. This isn't just about asking questions. This is about having an agent that proactively researches topics around the clock and surfaces insights to you. Here's how I have this set up. My research agent monitors specific subreddits, Twitter accounts, and news sources. When it finds something relevant, it doesn't just save it. It analyzes it, synthesizes it, and sends me a digest with actionable insights. The key difference is that my agent understands my specific context. It knows I'm a content creator in the AI space. It knows I'm building products. It knows my goals. So when it researches, it's not bringing back random information. It's bringing back information that's relevant to where I'm trying to go. This has been absolutely game changing for staying ahead of trends. I feel like I have a full research team working for me while I sleep. The second use case is using Claudebot as a writing partner, not just a writer. Most people use AI to write for them. That's fine, but you're missing out on the real power. When you use Claudebot as a writing partner, you engage in a dialogue. You bounce ideas off each other. You iterate together. Here's my workflow. When I have a piece to write, I don't just say write this. Instead, I say here's my rough idea. What angles should I explore? What points should I hit? Then we discuss. Claudebot brings up points I hadn't considered. I push back on some of its suggestions. We iterate. By the time we actually write the piece, it's so much better than what either of us would have produced alone. This collaborative approach has dramatically improved my content. The third use case is using Claudebot for automated code review. I know many of you use it for coding, but are you using it for code review? This is different from having it write code. This is having it critically analyze code you've written or code that you need to review and provide deep insights. Here's my setup. I have a code review agent that's separate from my coding agent. This agent specializes in spotting issues, bugs, security vulnerabilities, performance problems, and architectural concerns. When my coding agent finishes a piece of work, it automatically gets passed to the review agent. The review agent looks it over and either approves it or sends it back with detailed feedback. This has caught so many issues before they became problems. It's like having a senior engineer on staff who reviews everything. The fourth use case is using Claudebot as a personal knowledge manager. This is about building a second brain that actually works. Most people try to build second brains and fail because they can't keep up with the maintenance. With Claudebot, the agent maintains it for you. Here's how it works. Everything I read, everything I write, every meeting I have, every idea I have, gets captured. Claudebot organizes it, tags it, and connects it to related concepts. When I need to find something, I just ask. What's my thinking on prompt engineering? It'll pull up all my notes, all my past discussions, everything I've said about it across all my conversations. This has been incredible for creative work. When I'm developing new ideas, Claudebot can show me related ideas I've had in the past, connections I hadn't considered, and relevant research I've forgotten about. The fifth use case is using Claudebot for automated testing. This is different from just having AI write tests. This is having an agent that designs test strategies, identifies edge cases you haven't considered, and ensures your code is robust. Here's my approach. When I finish a feature, my testing agent goes to town on it. It thinks about all the ways users could break this. It thinks about boundary conditions, error states, race conditions, security concerns. It doesn't just run the tests you ask it to run. It designs the tests itself based on a deep understanding of what your code is trying to do. This has dramatically reduced bugs in my code. The sixth and most important use case is using Claudebot as a strategic advisor. This is about having an agent that doesn't just execute tasks but helps you think about strategy, priorities, and direction. Here's how I use this. Every week, I have a strategy session with my advisor agent. We discuss where I'm at, where I want to go, what's working, what's not. The agent brings data. It has insights from monitoring all my projects. It has perspectives I haven't considered. It challenges my assumptions. This has been absolutely invaluable for making better decisions. I feel like I have a world-class advisor available to me 24/7. The key to all of these use cases is thinking about Claudebot differently. Most people think of it as a tool, like a calculator or a search engine. That's wrong. You should think of it as an employee. It's a team member who can think, can learn, can remember, can execute. When you start thinking about it this way, the possibilities become endless. You can delegate, you can collaborate, you can build entire organizations of agents that work together. I hope these six use cases gave you some ideas. If you want to learn more about any of these, drop a comment below. And if you found this video valuable, please like and subscribe. I'll see you in the next one.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774924518578}}
{"type":"message","id":"b45e72b1","parentId":"f5882dcd","timestamp":"2026-03-31T02:35:18.585Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_bbbtfmn77k40_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"---\nVideo URL: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ev4iiGXlnh0\n---\n\nTranscript:\n\nClaudebot is blowing up everywhere and for good reason. Almost everyone agrees it's the most powerful AI tool ever created. A literal 247 AI employee. The issue is there's almost no agreement on the correct way to set it up. Half of people are running out and buying $600 Mac minis. The other half are crying and say, \"Hey, you're wasting your money. Set this up for free on a VPS.\" In this video, I'm going to go through every single way you can be setting up Claudebot and show you why I think the Mac Mini is actually the right way to be doing this. I'm also going to tell you why I'm returning my Mac Mini. Yeah, let's get into this. So, I'm going to be going through every single way you could be setting up Claudebot. By the end of this video, you know exactly the right way for you to be doing it. Even if you already have Claudebot set up, you'll be able to know if you set it up the right way and if you should switch to another device or another service. I'm going to go through every way you could be doing it. Whether it's the Mac Mini or an old dusty laptop in your closet or a VPS or one of these one-click launch services that are popping up. I feel like there's a hundred of them. Now, I'm going to go through the strengths and weaknesses for each and you will be all good to go to get the most out of Claudebot by the end of this video. So, stick around with me here. Let's start with the Mac Mini and the VPS. I feel like these are the two most popular ways people are setting up their Clawbots. That's how I set up mine was with the Mac Mini. But, I feel like most people are saying, \"Hey, you're wasting your money. Go with the VPS.\" Well, here are the strengths and weaknesses of those two. So, right off the rip, Mac Mini, it's starting at $600. I don't think you need an expensive Mac Mini. The ones that are more than $600. I think you can get away with a base one, but $600 is still a lot for a lot of people. On the VPS side, this is the virtual private server side. This is like the Amazon EC2s and other virtual private servers. They are cheap. You can get away with using this for free on Amazon EC2. I even had a video about setting it up on the Amazon EC2. I'll link to that down below. But you can get away with using that for free. From a cost perspective, the VPS might be the strongest out of all of them. But here's where the strengths of the Mac Mini come in and the weaknesses of the VPS. The Mac Mini is secure by default. By default, when you set up Claudebot on a Mac Mini, it has access to nothing. It can't leak anything because it's not connected to anything. It's not public facing. So, by default, the Mac Mini is extremely secure. By default, the VPS is not secure. In fact, it is the least secure of all these ones that we have up here. Now, by default, there is no security set up with a VPS. When you put this on Amazon EC2, that server instance is public to the entire internet. Meaning, if you set up your Clogbot in there, people can access your keys. That is not good. That means people can steal your keys and use all your services and charge you thousands of dollars. In order to secure a VPS, you need to do a whole bunch of technical things. You need to install SSH and firewalls and a whole bunch of other things. For the average person, that is too complex. and I wouldn't recommend doing it. On top of that, the VPS is extremely hard to interact with. It's just a CLI in your browser. For most people, they don't want to sit there and their way of engaging with an AI agent just talking to a CLI. On top of that, it doesn't integrate, right? So, if you want to send it a photo or an image or a video, it's going to be extremely difficult to do. As for the Mac Mini, it's extremely easy to interact with. I would argue that Mac OS is the most userfriendly operating system of them all. It takes seconds to get into and there's a reason why it's the most popular OS. It's also fully integrated. So if you have other Apple devices like I have an iPhone for instance, I have an iPad, I have a MacBook Pro. Anytime I want to give my 247 AI employee agent a file, whether it's a photo or a video or anything, all I have to do is click a button and I can airdrop that file to my Mac Mini that has my Clawbot on it. So for instance, if I want to make the thumbnail for this video, all I need to do is airdrop the video to my Claudebot. say, \"Hey, check out the video. Look at the transcript and create me a thumbnail.\" It and it can go and do that. So, it is fully integrated into my entire workflow, which is really amazing and like honestly like 90% of the value. Anyway, on top of that, you can use all the modern AI tools with it. So, one of the strengths of the Claudebot is it is a basically a human employee. It can do anything a human being can do. All these AI companies, the tools they come out with, they drop on Apple first. They come out on Apple products first. So your Clawbot can leverage all those powerful AI tools that drop like the new codecs that just dropped for instance. It's only on Apple. So by getting a Mac Mini, you're going to have all the modern tools. I believe by going with a VPS like Amazon EC2, you are absolutely destroying your experience with Cloudbot just so that you can save a couple dollars. You're putting a really insecure instance of Claudebot on the internet that people can hack. you're having a really unpleasant experience using Claudebot, which I feel like 90% of this is like just having fun and using the Claudebot and engaging with it and talking with it and it doesn't integrate with any of your tools. So, it's really limiting its strength. This is why I went with the Mac Mini. But, as I'm going to go over a little bit later in this video, I'm actually returning my Mac Mini and you'll see why. And it might be the best option for you as well to not go with the Mac Mini. But, for 90% of people, I think the Mac Mini is the correct way to go. As for the VPS, I'd put at zero% of people. I think VPS is the wrong choice for basically everyone on planet Earth. And I think the people going with the VPS and preaching for the VPS are like trying to take some sort of contrarian stance cuz they don't like it when big Apple sells Mac minis. I just don't understand why anyone would go with the VPS. So then you have the one-click launch services. There are a ton of these out there. I'm not going to name them all, but these are like brand new companies that have basically spun up over the last week that are basically, hey, we'll make it super easy to install Cloudbot on the cloud. All you got to do is click one button. And they do have some strengths. They're cheap. They're also like $15 a month. They are super easy. You literally click one button and you have it set up on their cloud and their servers. It is also more secure. They kind of set up their own guard rail, so it is very secure on their servers. But for me, the issues are dealreaking. Again, you have to log into a browser, then log onto a server to interact with this AI agent. A lot of the power of Claudebot comes from the fact that it's living on your computer. You can watch it work. You can watch it click on your different files, open up browsers, interact with the internet. When you have it on these one-click services, they're on some sort of server you can't see. So, that eliminates, again, like 90% of the value. It's not powerful because it's not integrated with all your tools and all your computer. It's not integrated with all your files, all your videos, all your photos, all your memories. It's not integrated with any of that. So, all the power is taken away from it as well. And listen, this is a competition. If your Claudebot's going up against someone else's Clawbot and they have access to all the tools, all the powerful AI tools out there and yours doesn't, you're not going to win. You want to have a powerful Clawbot. And on top of that, it's unreliable. I have tried setting up the one-click Clawbot on like five different services. Four of them just straight up didn't work. and it crashed and it wouldn't give me any reason why. It didn't load up. It didn't remember a lot of things I needed to remember. It just wasn't a very usable service. So, I'd say the one-click launch services are just about as useless as the VPS. So, now we have the dusty computer in your closet and the Mac Studio. Dusty computer in your closet is basically any computer out there that's cheap, whether you have it in your closet or you run out and buy some Linux computer or cheap HP or Chromebook or something like that. And Mac Studio is basically any expensive AI computer. the Mac Studio, the DGX Spark, the Tiny Box, anything that's super powerful and has tons of GPU and memory inside of it. You can I'm basically using that as substitute names. This dusty computer in your closet is an excellent option. I'm not going to tell anyone they shouldn't be using that old HP laptop in their closet. It's the cheapest. You already have it. It's free, so you might as well take it out. It's local, so you're running your Claudebot locally, not on some server in the cloud. So again, it's more secure by default, and it's totally customizable. It's your own computer, so you can give it any tools you want or have it do anything you want. The downsides are it's a tad less secure. So, for instance, if you're using an old computer that's logged into your email, your messaging services, your Twitter account, your YouTube, when you boot up your Clawbot, it's going to by default have access to all of those accounts, right? So, if you're Claudebot, you accidentally give it a prompt you didn't want to