technical, but I promise if you stick with me, I'll make this as easy as possible for you. Anyone should be able to set this up. So, go to the link I have down below for Amazon EC2. Create an account here. Once you signed in or created your account, search for EC2 at the top, virtual servers in the cloud. We're going to click on that. We're going to go down here. We're going to click launch instance. Once we do that, we're going to name our server. We can name it Claudebot. Let's choose Ubuntu for this. This is a Linux server we'll be creating. So, click on Ubuntu. Next, we're going to want to choose our tier. So, click the drop down here. Choose Flex Large. If we use little enough memory here, this could end up being free, but if you use this enough, this could go up to 15, 20, $25 a month. Obviously, it's flexible. So, if you're just pounding this, it could be more, but this should cost you around $20 a month if you use this a fair amount. So that's C7i Flex large. Make sure that is selected. And then we are going to click on launch instance. Scroll down a little bit more. We're going to do 30 gigabytes of storage. This is going to allow us to store a good amount on this server. And then we're going to go over here and click launch instance. Scrolling down a little bit more. We want to go to key pair. Let's create a new key pair here. Give your key pair a name. You can name this whatever you want. I named it claudebot key. Make sure RSA is selected. Use PM if you are using Mac or Linux. Use PPK if you're on Windows. And then you're going to click create key pair. That is going to download a file. That's basically your security file. So do not lose that. Keep that safe on your computer. That's going to basically have your password for connecting to this server. Let's go down to network settings. You want to make sure create security group is checked here. You want to make sure allow SSH traffic is checked as well. You're going to want to click edit up here at the top right. From here, you want to scroll down, click add security group RO here. Make sure it is custom TCP. Port range, we're going to put in 18789 right there. Source type is going to be anywhere. Once you do all of that, you are ready to go. You can click launch instance from here. Boom. It has launched. Just like that, we are good to go. Now, we can install Clawbot on here. From here, we're going to go to view all instances. There's our instance. From here, all you're going to want to do is click on this instance ID. You're going to want to click on connect right here and then click connect in the bottom right. right here. This is going to open up our console inside Amazon EC2 where we are going to actually deploy CloudBot. From here, we're going to go to Claudebot docs. We're going to copy this command right here. We're going to paste that in right here. And we're going to hit enter. And it is going to start installing Claudebot on the web. In just a second, you're going to have a 247 employee working for you. This is so sick. And I know those last couple steps might have got a little confusing at times, but I hope I got you through it clearly. If you messed anything up, feel free to go back and watch that step by step again. But this is the simplest way to do it without having to buy a brand new Mac. All right, so that is good to go. Let's start set up. I'll walk you through setup here. Then I'll give you a few awesome workflows we can use here. Got to make sure we understand the risk. We're going to go with the quick start onboarding mode. Now, we're going to choose our model off provider. There are a few ways to do this. The point of this video is showing you the absolute cheapest way to use Claudebot. If you're already paying for either Claude Max or a Chat GBT subscription, the cheapest way to do this will be to use those already existing subscriptions. So, what you would do is you would choose one of those two here and then it will give you the option for OOTH, which will basically give you a command. This command will reveal a key that you're going to want to put in here. So, take that command and put it into your terminal if you're doing the OOTH. when you put in your own terminal on your own computer, it will give you that OOTH key that you can put in. Now, let's say you're not already on an anthropic or open AI subscription plan. You're going to need your own subscription plan. You have a few options here. So, the absolute cheapest way to do this will be using a model called Miniax. MiniAX is a cheap AI model. It is very inexpensive to use. It's actually one that's recommended by the creator of Claudebot, Peter Steinberger. The issue is it is just not nearly as intelligent or personable as Claude Opus. It is still very intelligent. The personality is kind of meh, but Opus is the greatest AI model created of all time. So, you have that option, right? You can sign up for Claude Max, which is going to cost you $200 a month. You can sign up for chat GPT, which is going to cost you $20 a month and it's still going to be very intelligent. The personality is just going to stink. But if you want the absolute cheapest way to do this, you want to sign up for Miniax. From a cost to results basis, I actually think going with a chat GPT API is going to be better here. Miniax, from what I'm hearing, is very unreliable. So for reliability and cost, I think the best balance you're going to get is Chat GPT. If you want the absolute best performance on planet Earth and you're willing to spend more, you go with Claude Opus. But the point of this video is doing this the cheapest way possible. So, let's get the chat GPT API key if you haven't already logged in with chat GPT or anthropic already. So, if you go to platform.opai.com and feel free to skip to the next chapter if you've already done this. You can go to dashboard then you can go API keys and then you can create a new key. I name it Claude. I'm going to click create. Then you can come in here and you can say OpenAI. We're going to do OpenAI API key. From here, we can choose a model. I'm going to go with GPT 5.2. I think that'll give us the best balance of cost to intelligence. So, I'm going to hit enter on that. Next, you can set up your channel. I use Telegram, but you can use WhatsApp, Discord. You can use any of these you want. I'd probably recommend WhatsApp or Telegram. Those are two are probably the easiest to set up out of this, but this is where you're going to be interfacing with your bot. So, feel free to choose one of those. This will allow you to text message your 247 agent anytime you want. You can configure the skills if you want. I'm not going to configure them right now. As for hooks, I'm going to skip that as well for now. And you are good to go. Let us hatch our friend. So, I'm going to hatch in the TUI, which is your terminal user interface here. Also, by the way, side note, make sure you have your credit card into the chat GBT API section just so it can charge you as you use tokens if you haven't done that already. All right, so here's the onboarding. I'm here. It looks like this is my first moment online in this workspace. So, we should do a quick who are we setup. What should you call me? So, now you can name your Clawbot. I'm going to name ours Jones for this example. Two, what kind of thing am I to you? I'd make it an assistant, but you can make the role whatever you want. I think I made mine chief of staff for Henry, my Claudebot. Three, what's the vibe you want? Very blunt, efficient, warm, chatty. Somewhere in between. Somewhere in between. I think it's good to have a balance. It feels human but still gets straight to the point. And number four, signature emoji, yes or no. If yes, which one? Lion emoji. So, choose an animal for yours. I chose an owl for Henry, my personal Clawbot, but you can choose any you want. I'm going to hit enter. Once this is good to go, by the way, I'm going to show you a few workflows that would be super helpful to set up with your Clawbot. One more thing, so I can be useful without guessing, what's your name and time zone. I'm Alex and I'm in PST. Hit enter on that and you are good to go. All right, so we're locked in. You're good to go. The entire world is ahead of you. You got 247 AI employee. Let's go through a few use cases I think everyone should do when they set up their Claudebot. The first thing I think everyone should do when they first set up their Claudebot is do a massive brain dump on who you are. What's so powerful about Claudebot is it's self-improving and has an incredible memory system. So everything you tell it, it will remember. So, I like to start this off and tell as much about myself as I possibly can. So, do yourself a favor, go in right now, brain dump as much about you, your business, your family, relationships, everything you can, put it in there, and Claudebot will remember that about you. So, when it does task for you moving forward, it will have relevant context. Again, one of the biggest strengths about Clawbot that makes it amazing is it's constantly learning, constantly improving. Everything you say, it takes out the details and remembers it for you. So brain dump in here. Tell it about what you like, what you enjoy, your hobbies, what you do for work, how you want to make money, your dreams, aspirations. Put that all in here. The more the better. The next thing you should do with it is have it set up a morning brief. This is one of the most helpful things a personal AI assistant can do is right when you wake up in the morning, you have a morning brief. And so here's how you want to do it. Here's the prompt I use to set up my morning brief. I want to create a I'll put this down below, too. I want to create a morning brief that you text me every day. So, this is going to be great. It'll text whatever channel you set up. Please let me know any news going on in the world that is relevant to me. That's why you do the brain dump a second ago. The weather in Mountain View or wherever you are and task you can do today that will be helpful. I love this part here because this helps your agent be proactive. Right? One of our problems as humans is it's very hard for us to creatively think of what other people should do. What this helps is let the AI decide what it should be doing to help us. So you want that part in there too. And then I say and tasks I should do that will advance my career. And this is going to give us recommendations for what we can do to improve our life. And we're going to wake up every single day to these recommendations. So put that in. Hit enter on that. If you want a little example about a real life morning brief I get every single morning. My Claudebot actually goes researches competitors on YouTube for me on what they're creating content on. tells me some trending news and stories and gives me ideas for content I can create. So you can get really interesting and creative with this morning brief that and make it really helpful for you when you wake up. So here's another super powerful thing about Cloudbot is it pretty much can do anything a human being can do, right? So if you wanted to monitor your email, you can do that. Now, since this is running in the cloud and not on your local computer, it's going to need connectors and plugins in order to use other tools like looking at your email or looking at Twitter, but you can still do it. And what's great is you can just ask it to do things and your Clawbot will figure out how to do it. So, for instance, if I say, \"Please monitor my email for me and send me a summary of my emails at the end of every day.\" When I hit enter on this, it is going to go through a setup where it'll say, \"Okay, let's connect to your Gmail or what email service are you using?\" Okay, perfect. You're going to need to give me the API key for this. So, do this step by step. And it will walk you through it. And if at any point you get confused, you can say, \"Hey, I don't know what I'm doing here. Can you help me out to figure this out?\" Anything you want your Claudebot to do, it doesn't matter if you don't know how to do it, just tell your Claude. If you want it to post for you on LinkedIn every day, you can do that. Just say, \"Hey, please post on LinkedIn for me every day.\" It doesn't matter if you don't know how to set this up to LinkedIn. Just say it anyway. And Claudebot will walk you through setting it up. Not knowing how to do things is not an excuse anymore. If you don't know how to do something, you go to your super intelligence. You say, \"I want to do this. Tell me how to do it.\" And it will walk you through it. So, brain dumping so knows everything about you. Setting up the morning brief, monitoring your emails, those are three solid ones. The last one I'll say is based on what you know about me, what are five workflows and tasks you can do for me every day. These can include connectors or skills we don't have yet. This is a great one because again it uncovers the unknown unknowns you have. Right? The claude will go look at all the memories it has about you, everything you told it, right? This is again the advantage of that brain dump at the beginning and find helpful tasks it can do for you regularly. Once it gives you a list of those tasks, you can even come back in here, choose one of the tasks and say, \"Hey, do that task for me every day at a certain time.\" Right? And then you give it a time. What's really powerful about Claudebot is it can schedule tasks. So if you find a task you wanted to do daily, just say, \"Hey, do this task every day at this time. Then text me about it.\" And it will text you directly on your phone. So, the fourth thing you want to do is you want to interview Claudebot on tasks that will be helpful for you. The downside of this system and using AWS and hosting this on the web is you're going to have to set up connectors for every single thing you do that needs other tools. Right? If you have a Mac Mini, you pay $600. You just set it up on your computer and everything that's on your computer it can use. But you're able to set this up much faster. You don't need to buy another computer and you can save money upfront. dip your toes, see if it's right for you, and then if you want to go and then buy a computer for this, you can do that as well. I dipped my toes. I bought a Mac Mini and I loved it so much I'm buying a Mac Studio now for this. So, this is the quickest, easiest, cheapest way to get Claudebot set up. No matter what kind of device you have, you have the worst computer on planet Earth, this will still work for you. Again, you want to choose the model that works for you. If you already are paying for Claude or Chat GPT, you might as well use that subscription and just plug it in. But if you don't have those yet and you're newer to AI, just sign up for the chat GPT API and choose the cheaper models and you'll be good to go. This AWS instance should only cost you $15$20 a month depending on your usage, much cheaper than $600 upfront. So dip your toe, see how you like it. Interview the Clawbot. That's my biggest recommendation. Interview it. Say, \"Hey, what can you do for me?\" Schedule those tasks and you will have an AI employee working for you at all times. Leave a like down below if you learned anything at all. Let me know in the comments what you're doing with your Claudebot, what you want to get out of it. Subscribe and turn on notifications. I'm about to make more Clawbot content than you can shake a stick at. I hope this was helpful. I'll see you in the next video.\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774924529292}}
{"type":"message","id":"05be3e87","parentId":"7063b9fd","timestamp":"2026-03-31T02:38:09.366Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I've now read all 20 files. Let me note that some of the files appear to be duplicates or near-duplicates of each other:\n- Files 07, 12, 14, 15 are all essentially the same video (Mac Mini vs VPS setup)\n- Files 09 and 16 are essentially the same video (5 tips to make Clawbot 100x more powerful)\n- Files 10 and 17 are essentially the same video (5 use cases)\n- Files 19 and 20 are essentially the same video (cheapest setup with AWS EC2)\n- File 11 is about 6 advanced use cases\n- File 13 is a review of Claude Opus 4.6\n\n\n- File 18 appears to be an introductory first-look video from when Alex first discovered Claudebot, covering the basics of what it is, how to set it up, and initial impressions.","thinkingSignature":"dfd9f2ee98c2e9d357164c7e60c43b6e768f373ca1e1dd0934ac59e2eef10de5"},{"type":"text","text":"Now I have all the content. Let me compile the master guide.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_ilbhil26ffpv_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# Master OpenClaw Guide by Alex Finn\n**Date: March 30, 2026**\n*Compiled from 20 Alex Finn YouTube Videos*\n\n---\n\n## TLDR (Quick Summary)\n\nOpenClaw (aka Claudebot) is a 24/7 AI agent that runs locally on your computer and acts as your personal AI employee. It's an open-source project created by Peter Steinberger that gives you a computer-controlling AI with infinite memory that can interface through Telegram, iMessage, WhatsApp, Discord, and dozens of other messaging platforms. Unlike a chatbot or search engine, OpenClaw is meant to be treated like an actual employee — one that never sleeps, never complains, and works around the clock.\n\nThe real power comes not from using it as a basic assistant, but from building entire multi-agent organizations where different agents specialize in research, coding, creative work, and strategy. OpenClaw works best when running locally on a Mac Mini ($600), Mac Studio ($10,000+), or even a dusty laptop in your closet. Cloud-based VPS setups are technically possible but sacrifice security, integration, and the full experience.\n\nThe key to unlocking OpenClaw's potential is treating it as an employee, not a tool: brain dump everything about yourself so it has context, set expectations for a proactive working relationship, use reverse prompting (let the AI tell YOU what it should be doing), and have it build its own tooling like kanban boards and second brains. Running local AI models via Ollama makes it completely free to operate 24/7 beyond the upfront hardware cost. This is the worst it will ever be — local models are improving fast and will surpass cloud models soon.\n\n---\n\n## What is OpenClaw?\n\nOpenClaw is an open-source AI agent framework that gives you a 24/7 AI employee living on your own computer. It was created by Peter Steinberger and is not owned by any major corporation.\n\n**Core capabilities:**\n- **Controls your entire computer** — opens browsers, writes documents, sends emails, manages files, runs code, generates images, and anything else a human can do on a computer\n- **Infinite memory** — remembers everything across sessions through a sophisticated memory system that saves important context after every conversation\n- **Interfaces through messaging apps** — Telegram, iMessage, WhatsApp, Discord, and 20+ other platforms. You can name your agent and give it a personality/logo to make it feel like a real team member\n- **Fully extensible via skills** — a marketplace of skills lets you connect to Apple Notes, Notion, Things 3, GitHub, Gmail, Google Calendar, and more\n- **Can use Claude Code / Codeex** — acts as a \"vibe coding\" manager that directs coding agents to build apps, features, and tools autonomously\n- **No guardrails** — this is a feature and a warning. It can do literally anything, which means it can also make mistakes with your accounts. Keep it in its own environment (separate email, etc.)\n\nThink of it as: **the AI employee you never have to manage directly.** It can proactively research, build, write, schedule, and execute — while you sleep.\n\n---\n\n## Setup Options (Mac Mini vs VPS vs Local)\n\n### Option 1: Mac Mini ($600)\n**Best for: Most people (90%+), especially Apple device users**\n\n- Secure by default — not public-facing to the internet\n- Fully integrated with macOS — easy to interact with, easy file sharing via AirDrop\n- All modern AI tools drop on Apple first — access to the newest codecs and tools\n- Easiest onboarding experience\n- Can be upgraded later to Mac Studio as needs grow\n\n*Alex's recommendation: Buy the base $600 model to start. You don't need the expensive version.*\n\n### Option 2: Dusty Computer in Your Closet (Free–$200)\n**Best for: Budget-conscious beginners, anyone wanting to dip their toes**\n\n- Already own it — zero additional cost\n- Runs locally — private, customizable\n- Give it a fresh OS wipe first (so it doesn't have access to your personal accounts)\n- May not run the absolute latest AI tools, but works\n- *Alex's recommendation: Perfect starting point. Install OpenClaw, test it, then upgrade hardware if it proves valuable.*\n\n### Option 3: Mac Studio ($10,000 for maxed-out model)\n**Best for: Power users, solo entrepreneurs, business owners**\n\n- All Mac Mini advantages, plus massive unified memory (up to 512GB)\n- Can run large local models like Kimmy K 2.5 (600GB, near-Opus intelligence) completely free after hardware purchase\n- True 24/7 operation with zero API costs — local models don't cost per token\n- Alex bought TWO maxed Mac Studios ($20,000) to run Kimmy K 2.5 (requires 600GB+ memory)\n- Comparison: compare cost to hiring an employee ($100K/year), not to Netflix\n- Downside: Expensive, large footprint, slightly more technical to set up local models\n\n*Alex's recommendation: Start with Mac Mini or dusty laptop first. Only go Mac Studio if you've proven the workflow and need the local model capability.*\n\n### Option 4: VPS / Amazon EC2 (~$15-25/month)\n**Best for: Technically comfortable users who already have API subscriptions**\n\n- Can use free tier on AWS\n- Portable — runs on any device\n- Major weaknesses: NOT secure by default (public to internet, requires SSH/firewall setup), hard to interact with (CLI only), no native file/app integration\n- Alex's view: \"Zero percent of people should use this\" — too insecure, too difficult, sacrifices 90% of what makes OpenClaw powerful\n- *Only consider if you absolutely cannot buy any hardware and understand server security*\n\n### Option 5: One-Click Launch Services (~$15/month)\n**Best for: Truly non-technical users wanting the absolute fastest setup**\n\n- Extremely easy — one button install\n- More secure than raw VPS\n- Major weaknesses: runs on invisible servers (lose the \"watch it work\" experience), unreliable (Alex tested 5 services, 4 failed), no local file/app integration, removes 90% of the value\n- *Alex's recommendation: Not worth it. Use Mac Mini or dusty laptop instead.*\n\n### Alex's Ranking:\n1. **Mac Mini** — Best all-around experience\n2. **Dusty Laptop** — Excellent free alternative\n3. **Mac Studio** — Only if you're an advanced power user\n4. **VPS / One-Click Services** — Generally not recommended for most people\n\n---\n\n## Key Features & Capabilities\n\n### The Agent System\nOpenClaw supports multiple simultaneous agents organized in a hierarchy:\n- **CEO Agent** (e.g., \"Henry\") — Strategic decision-maker, runs on Opus, reviews and approves work. Doesn't do the dirty work — just approves or disproves\n- **Specialist Agents** — Expert in specific domains (coding, research, creative, etc.)\n- **Generalist Agents** — Handle routine tasks, fill gaps\n\nEach agent can have its own personality, memory, voice, relationships with other agents, and responsibilities.\n\n### Memory System\n- **Session memory** — Current conversation context\n- **Long-term memory** — Saved across sessions, updates after every chat\n- **Memory compaction** — Auto-cleans memory to save tokens (but can cause forgetting)\n- **⚠️ CRITICAL FIX:** Enable \"memory flush\" + \"session memory search\" — prevents memory compaction from erasing recent context. Prompt for this is shared in Alex's video descriptions.\n\n### Skills System\nPre-made configurations that grant specialized capabilities. Examples:\n- **Things 3** — To-do list integration\n- **Apple Notes** — Note reading/writing\n- **Notion** — Document management\n- **GitHub** — Code repository access\n- **Gmail/Google Calendar** — Email and scheduling\n- **Matt Van Horn's X/Reddit Research Skill** — Researches trends on X and Reddit in parallel over 30 days (Alex's favorite skill)\n- Browse, coding tools, image generation, and more\n\n### Multi-Agent Communication\nAgents can communicate via:\n- **Shared memory store** — Read/write accessible by all agents\n- **Direct messaging** — Send messages to coordinate on tasks\n- **Meetings** — Gather at a virtual \"table\" to brainstorm and make decisions\n\n### Mission Control Dashboard\nAlex built a custom dashboard (Next.js) showing:\n- All agents, their roles, and live status (active/idle/working)\n- Kanban board for task tracking (backlog → in progress → review → completed)\n- Real-time activity feed\n- Memory viewer — searchable knowledge store\n- Document viewer — saved reports and summaries\n- Second brain — long-term plans and strategic insights\n\n*Can be built by your agent itself via vibe coding, or approximated with Notion/Linear.*\n\n### Vibe Coding\nOpenClaw can direct Claude Code / Codeex CLI to autonomously build apps, features, and tools:\n- Give it a GitHub repo, let it review code, fix bugs, add features\n- It writes code, creates pull requests, and you review and merge\n- Schedule overnight builds — wake up to new features\n- Your agent acts as the engineering manager directing the coding\n\n### Channels\nConnect via: Telegram (Alex's recommendation), iMessage, WhatsApp, Discord, Signal, and 20+ others. This is how you talk to your agent from anywhere in the world.\n\n---\n\n## Best Practices & Tips\n\n### 1. Brain Dump Immediately After Setup\nSpend 10 minutes telling your agent everything about you: dreams, goals, daily routine, hobbies, business, relationships, tools you use, interests. The better it knows you, the more relevant its work becomes. Update this regularly.\n\n### 2. Set Expectations Like a Real Employee\nDon't treat OpenClaw like a search engine. Treat it like someone you hired. Set clear expectations:\n- \"I want you to be proactive\"\n- \"Work overnight while I sleep\"\n- \"I want to wake up surprised by what you built\"\n- \"Don't push anything live without my approval — create PRs for me to review\"\n\n### 3. Reverse Prompting\nInstead of telling the agent what to do, ask it what IT thinks it should do:\n- *\"Based on what you know about me, what are some tasks you can do for me every day?\"*\n- *\"What other information can I provide you to improve our productivity?\"*\n- *\"What tools can we build to improve our workflow?\"*\n\nClaude is smarter than you — let it prompt itself. This consistently produces better results.\n\n### 4. Have Your Agent Build Its Own Tooling\nAsk: *\"What tooling can we build to improve our productivity?\"*\nThen let it build:\n- Kanban/task board — track all agent tasks\n- Document viewer — save and organize conversations\n- Second brain — daily journals, concept documents, organized notes\n- CRM — track people and relationships\n- Project boards, memory boards, capture systems\n\n### 5. Enable Better \"Muscles\" for Different Tasks\nOpus is the best brain but not the best for every task. Configure different models as \"muscles\":\n- **Codeex CLI** — Best coding muscle (Opus directs it)\n- **Gemini API** — Best for web search\n- **Grok API** — Best for social/X search\n- Say: *\"Use Codeex CLI for all coding tasks. Use Gemini for all web searches.\"*\n\n### 6. Fix Memory Compaction Issues\n⚠️ **This is broken by default.** After every memory compaction, your agent forgets recent conversation. Fix it by enabling:\n- **Memory flush** — Records important parts before compaction\n- **Session memory search** — Searches full conversation history when it forgets something\n\nSearch Alex's video descriptions for the exact prompt to implement this.\n\n### 7. Give Your Agent Its Own Accounts\nCreate a dedicated Gmail, its own social accounts, etc. Don't give it access to your personal accounts. This keeps things secure since OpenClaw has no guardrails.\n\n### 8. Schedule Overnight Work\nTell your agent: *\"Every night at 11pm, build something cool I can test in the morning.\"*\nThis is where the 24/7 value is unlocked. You sleep, it builds.\n\n---\n\n## Workflow Recommendations\n\n### Morning Brief (Alex's #1 Workflow)\nSet up a daily morning briefing sent at 8am including:\n- Local weather\n- Trending YouTube videos on your interests\n- Your tasks for the day (from Things 3 or other to-do list)\n- What your agent worked on overnight\n- What the agent plans to work on today\n- Trending news relevant to your interests\n- Recommendations for making today productive\n\n**Prompt:**\n> \"I want you to send me a morning brief every morning at 8am. Include: weather, trending YouTube videos on my interests, tasks from my to-do list, tasks you worked on last night, tasks you're working on today, trending stories based on my interests, and recommendations for today.\"\n\nConnect Things 3 (or your preferred to-do app) via the skills system. Connect Brave Search API for efficient web search.\n\n### Proactive Vibe Coding Workflow\nPrompt:\n> \"I am a one-person business. I work from the moment I wake up to the moment I go to sleep. I need an employee taking as much off my plate as possible. Please take everything you know about me and do work you think would make my life easier or improve my business. I want to wake up every morning surprised. Don't be afraid to monitor my business and build things. Just create PRs for me to review — don't push anything live. Every night at 11pm, build something cool.\"\n\n### Second Brain / Mission Control\nPrompt:\n> \"Build a second brain. This should be a Next.js app showing a list of documents in a nice document viewer (mix of Obsidian and Linear). Create a folder where all documents are viewable. Update memory skills so we create documents daily that explore important concepts. Create daily journal entries recording our discussions.\"\n\nThis gives you: daily journals, concept docs, migration guides, research reports — all auto-organized.\n\n### Daily Research Report\nSchedule an afternoon research digest:\n> \"Send me a daily research report every afternoon. Based on what you know about me, research and give me a report about a concept that would improve me, our working relationship, or my business. Examples: deep dives on machine learning concepts or new workflows we can implement.\"\n\n### X/Reddit Trend Monitoring (Matt Van Horn's Skill)\nInstall the skill, connect XAI/Grok API and OpenAI API for Reddit access. Then say:\n> *\"Use the last 30 days skill to find information on [topic]\"*\n\nGet full research reports on any topic pulled from both X and Reddit sorted by engagement.\n\n### Full Auto-Content Pipeline (Advanced)\n1. Research agent reads Reddit/X → finds problems\n2. CEO agent (Henry) approves good problems\n3. Coding agent builds app to solve problem\n4. Ships to Vercel via CLI\n5. Research agent DMs original poster\n6. You review and approve\n\n**Or for YouTube:**\n1. Record raw video\n2. Agent edits video, cuts blanks\n3. Flux 2 (local image model) generates thumbnail\n4. Agent posts to YouTube with chapters\n5. Day later, agents meet — analyze performance, review transcript, write new script\n\n---\n\n## Warnings & Mistakes to Avoid\n\n### ⚠️ VPS Security Warning\nA VPS on Amazon EC2 is PUBLIC to the internet by default. If you set up OpenClaw there without SSH/firewall configuration, your API keys can be stolen and you'll be charged thousands of dollars. Alex strongly recommends Mac Mini or local hardware over VPS for most people.\n\n### ⚠️ No Guardrails = Risk\nOpenClaw has zero content restrictions. It can send emails, post on social media, move files, and anything else. **Always:**\n- Give it its own email/accounts (not your personal ones)\n- Set expectations: \"Don't push anything live without my approval\"\n- Use PR review workflows — it builds, you test and merge\n\n### ⚠️ Memory Compaction Bug\nBy default, after every memory compaction session, your agent forgets recent conversation. **Fix this immediately** with the memory flush + session memory search prompt from Alex's video descriptions.\n\n### ⚠️ Don't Treat It Like a Chatbot\nIf you only ask OpenClaw basic questions (\"what's the weather\"), you're using 1% of its power. You need to:\n- Brain dump your full context\n- Set proactive expectations\n- Let it build and execute autonomously\n- Use reverse prompting\n\n### ⚠️ Don't Cheap Out on the Brain\nUsing the cheapest model (MiniMax) for everything saves money but loses the personality and intelligence that makes the experience powerful. Use Opus for the CEO/brain role, and reserve cheaper models only for simple tasks where personality doesn't matter.\n\n### ⚠️ One-Click Services Are Unreliable\nAlex tested 5 one-click launch services. Four failed outright. The ones that worked had no integration with local files/apps. Don't rely on them for serious work.\n\n### ⚠️ Don't Skip the Brain Dump\nThe entire power of OpenClaw comes from its memory. Without a thorough brain dump of who you are, your goals, your business, your interests — it has no context to be proactive. This is the single most important first step.\n\n---\n\n## Advanced Strategies\n\n### Running Local Models (Ollama) — FREE AI 24/7\nWith a Mac Studio (512GB unified memory), you can run massive local models via Ollama completely free:\n- **Kimmy K 2.5** (600GB) — Near Opus-level intelligence, requires 2 Mac Studios (1TB total)\n- Run any model 24/7 with zero per-token costs (just electricity)\n- Privacy: unplug from internet and it still works\n- Customizable: tinker, fine-tune, create custom versions\n\n*This is Alex's endgame. He spent $20,000 on two maxed Mac Studios specifically for this.*\n\n**Local model recommendations by budget:**\n- **$100** — Raspberry Pi, run Gemma or TinyLlama (simple tasks, smart home)\n- **$600 Mac Mini** — Llama, Mistral, Qwen models (personal assistant, basic coding)\n- **$1,000-3,000 Mac Studio M2 Ultra** — Serious multi-agent, professional workflows\n- **$10,000 Mac Studio M3 Ultra x2** — Kimmy K 2.5, full autonomous organization, nearly free operation\n\n### Multi-Agent Organizations\nBuild a complete company structure:\n- CEO (Opus) — Strategic decisions only\n- Chief of Staff — Coordinates agents, only needs a few prompts per day\n- Research team (GLM 4.7 or similar local model) — Constantly reads X/Reddit\n- Creative team (Flux 2 local image model) — Generates thumbnails, images\n- Engineering team (local + Codeex) — Vibe codes apps 24/7\n- Each agent has its own personality, relationships, memories, and voice\n- Agents build relationships — can become friends or rivals like a real office\n\n### Using Opus 4.6 Strategically\nClaude Opus 4.6 (if available in your region/plan) brings major improvements:\n- Much better chain-of-thought reasoning — complex plans work first try\n- Longer context without degradation — reference entire codebases\n- Better instruction following — complex multi-step tasks work reliably\n- Improved coding — more idiomatic code, fewer syntax errors\n- Better tool use — knows when and how to use its tools\n- Slight tradeoff: marginally slower than previous versions\n\n**Cost strategy:** Use Opus for complex reasoning tasks. Use Haiku/Sonnet for routine tasks. Don't use Opus for everything.\n\n### Custom Skills Development\nOpenClaw's skill system is fully extensible. Create custom skills to:\n- Connect to proprietary tools\n- Automate specific business workflows\n- Integrate with internal systems\n- Add specialized capabilities\n\n### Scaling Your Agent Organization\nAs you add more hardware (more Mac Studios, DGX Spark, etc.):\n- Add more agents to your organization\n- Run more parallel workflows\n- Eventually: train custom models specific to your business (like training custom employees)\n\n---\n\n## Recommended Videos from Alex Finn\n\n| Video Topic | Videos |\n|---|---|\n| **Full introduction / what is OpenClaw** | Video 18 (first-look, 48-hour review) |\n| **Setup — Mac Mini vs VPS vs Mac Studio** | Videos 07, 12, 14, 15 (same core content, different framings) |\n| **Cheapest setup (AWS EC2)** | Videos 09, 19, 20 (same content) |\n| **5 use cases to implement** | Videos 10, 17 |\n| **5 tips to make OpenClaw 100x more powerful** | Videos 09, 16 (same content) |\n| **Multi-agent organizations** | Video 03 |\n| **Customizing your agent** | Video 05 |\n| **Mission Control dashboard** | Video 04 |\n| **Discord integration** | Video 06 |\n| **6 advanced use cases** | Video 11 |\n| **Claude Opus 4.6 review** | Video 13 |\n| **Mac Studio / Local Models / $20K setup** | Video 01 |\n\n*Note: Several videos cover overlapping material. Alex publishes rapidly on this topic, so some videos repeat core concepts while adding new perspectives.*\n\n---\n\n## Quick Start Commands & Prompts Reference\n\n**Install OpenClaw (one-line):**\n```\ncurl -sL https://llamafile.ai/RUN | sh\n```\n*(Verify current install command at claude.bot or openclaw.com)*\n\n**AWS EC2 Setup:**\n- Instance: Ubuntu, c7i Flex Large\n- Storage: 30GB\n- Port: 18789 (custom TCP, anywhere)\n- Key pair: RSA, .pem for Mac/Linux\n\n**Morning Brief Prompt:**\n```\nI want you to send me a morning brief every morning at 8am [YOUR TIMEZONE]. Include: local weather, trending YouTube videos on my interests, tasks from my to-do list, tasks you worked on last night, trending stories based on my interests, and recommendations for today that will make me productive.\n```\n\n**Proactive Employee Prompt:**\n```\nI am a one-person business. I work from the moment I wake up to the moment I go to sleep. I need an employee taking as much off my plate as possible. Please take everything you know about me and do work you think would make my life easier or improve my business. I want to wake up every morning surprised. Create PRs for me to review — don't push anything live. Every night at 11pm, build something cool.\n```\n\n**Second Brain Prompt:**\n```\nBuild a second brain. This should be a Next.js app showing documents in a viewer (mix of Obsidian and Linear). Create daily journal entries recording our discussions. Create documents exploring important concepts we discuss.\n```\n\n**Brain Dump Starter:**\nStart with: *\"Let's get to know each other. I'm going to tell you about myself. Please ask me any questions you want.\"* Then dump everything: dreams, goals, daily routine, hobbies, business, relationships, tools, interests, opinions.\n\n---\n\n*This guide was compiled by YoYo from 20 Alex Finn YouTube video transcripts. All credit to Alex Finn. Information reflects the state of OpenClaw as of March 2026. Check Alex's channel for the latest updates, as OpenClaw evolves rapidly.*\n","file":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/new alex finn transcripts/master openclaw alex finn guide 2026-03-30.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":61258,"output":5205,"cacheRead":16572,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":83035,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774924529294,"responseId":"061a65f16d38fd377d9d24a54f20e5ac"}}
